        Hooker Furniture acquires Pulaski company
    


MICKEY POWELL | Bulletin Staff Writer

Jan 6, 2016
 (…)


























































































Hooker Furniture, based in Martinsville, announced Wednesday that it will make its largest acquisition in its 91-year history.The company has agreed to buy Home Meridian International Inc. (HMI) for roughly $100 million.As a result of the purchase, Hooker’s corporate size will more than double – it will have about 900 employees worldwide – and it will be one of the top five players in the nationwide furniture market, company officials said.No jobs at either Hooker or HMI are expected to be eliminated due to the sale, said Paul B. Toms Jr., Hooker’s chairman and chief executive officer. No new jobs are expected to be created, either, he said.He estimated that the company has about 225 employees in the Martinsville-Henry County area.Although its headquarters remain in Martinsville, Hooker has not manufactured furniture locally since its wooden furniture plant closed eight years ago, Toms said in a phone interview.Hooker now “sells a lot of furniture sourced overseas,” he said, but it maintains upholstery plants in Bedford and Hickory, N.C.Its product lines include home entertainment, home office, accent, dining and bedroom furniture.Based in High Point, N.C., HMI is the parent company of five furniture makers, including Pulaski Furniture.Its brands “are all vibrant, well-run businesses,” Toms said.As part of the purchase, Hooker will acquire most of HMI’s assets and some of its liabilities, according to a company news release.The approximately $100 million sale price includes about $85 million in cash and about $15 million in newly-issued Hooker stock, the release stated.“Although Hooker Furniture Corp. has been debt-free for some time, we look at this acquisition as an excellent way to put excess capital to work and use our pristine balance sheet to layer in a manageable amount of low-cost debt,” Toms said in the release.It is anticipated that HMI will operate autonomously – with the same management team – as a division of Hooker which, with the acquisition, is expected to surpass the half-billion-dollar sales mark, the release stated.
“We are particularly impressed with the depth and experience of the HMI management team and excited about having this level of talent join us as we plan for the future,” Toms said.The companies had combined revenues of more than $550 million during the 12 months that ended Oct. 31, and total operating income for the two companies for the period was $35.6 million, according to the release.“While there will be no merger of operations or change in customer-facing services,” Toms said in the release, “we do see opportunity to improve each company by sharing best practices and looking for ways to work together to lower costs, improve efficiency and grow sales,” Toms said.“The HMI team is excited to join with Hooker Furniture Corp. to become one of the largest players in the (furniture) industry,” said HMI Chief Executive Officer George Revington. “The success of these two companies is directly related to how they serve their customers and the new combination will make us even more effective and provides a great platform for future growth.”Following the sale, Revington will report to Toms, the release stated.Hooker’s purchase of HMI is expected to be finalized between Feb. 1 and March 31, the release indicated. It noted that Hooker shareholders do not have to approve the sale.When the sale is completed, in addition to the Bedford and Hickory upholstery plants, the combined company will have showrooms in High Point and Ho Chi Minh City, Vietnam, as well as eight distribution centers in Virginia, North Carolina, California, China and Vietnam.




















































